From: Marshall Bloom <MBLOOM@atlas.niaid.nih.gov>
Date: Fri, 2 May 1997 15:44:15 -0400
The parvovirus, feline panleukopenia virus, might be a good possibility. It
has been around much longer than canine parvo and is known to affect the big
cats. There are very good vaccines available for this.
